{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539778"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:46:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:46:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16700"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16700"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.36,0.34,0.1,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9391"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66400"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9391"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16700"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51851"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"1476"},{"type":"tags","id":"2076"},{"type":"tags","id":"8875"},{"type":"tags","id":"9043"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22209"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35956"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49536"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66400"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 77-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a five-month history of blurred vision in his right eye. He has noticed flashing lights and floating spots, as well as fatigue, 7kg weight loss and itching of his skin. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Visual acuity is 6/18 in the right eye and 6/6 in the left eye. Fundoscopy reveals a pigmented, elevated choroidal mass in the right eye.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Computed tomography of the orbits","Magnetic resonance imaging of the orbits","B-scan ultrasonography","Fluorescein angiography","Fine needle aspiration biopsy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and signs suggestive of choroidal melanoma with likely liver metastasis, including visual disturbance, photopsia, and a pigmented choroidal mass. The choice of initial investigation is crucial for accurate diagnosis and staging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUveal melanomas are the most common primary intraocular cancer in adults, and they are typically aggressive with poor prognosis in later stages. Melanomas from the choroid is the most common of the uveal tract sites (which include the iris and the ciliary body). Patients may present with blurry vision, decreased visual field loss, floaters, photopsia or be asymptomatic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EB-scan ultrasonography\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line investigation for suspected choroidal melanoma. It can demonstrate characteristic features including acoustic hollowing, choroidal excavation, and orbital shadowing. It also allows accurate measurement of tumour dimensions, which is crucial for monitoring and treatment planning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography\u003C/strong\u003E of the orbits is less useful as an initial investigation as it provides less detail of the choroidal lesion compared to ultrasound. While it can show calcification and extraocular extension, it exposes the patient to radiation and is more expensive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging\u003C/strong\u003E of the orbits is useful for evaluating extraocular extension and may be required later in the diagnostic workup, but it is not the first-line investigation. It is particularly helpful in determining the relationship of the tumour to surrounding structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluorescein angiography\u003C/strong\u003E can help differentiate choroidal melanoma from other conditions but is not the most appropriate initial investigation. It may show characteristic features such as double circulation but is less useful for measuring tumour dimensions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E carries a risk of tumour seeding and is generally reserved for cases where the diagnosis remains uncertain after imaging. It is not appropriate as a first-line investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce the diagnosis is confirmed, systemic staging with CT chest, abdomen, and pelvis is required as uveal melanoma commonly metastasises to the liver in approximately 90% of cases and prognosis is poor with metastasis. Regular monitoring with liver function tests and imaging is also necessary during follow-up.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ultrasound is the initial imaging modality of choice for suspected choroidal melanoma as it can demonstrate characteristic features and measure tumour dimensions.","MRI of the orbit is useful for evaluating extraocular extension of uveal melanoma."],"references":["Soliman N, Mamdouh D, Elkordi A. Choroidal Melanoma: A Mini Review. Medicines (Basel). 2023.  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9863301/","Shields C et al. Choroidal and Ciliary Body Melanoma.  American Academy of Ophthalmology EyeWiki. 2024.  Available at: https://eyewiki.org/Choroidal_and_Ciliary_Body_Melanoma"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51851"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16700"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51851"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T23:35:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-13T14:08:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9391"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66400"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T0